'Information' is an ill-defined concept at this level, and might well not
be fundamental, it's unlikely anyway, given that we are in a position of
trying to define it. The only statement I can make about it before I start
saying lots of stuff and getting lost, is that I mean a pattern that is not
just derived by our awareness of it. It would therefore include the
uncertain pattern.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; The key is that the outcome of a random event does not yet exist,
&gt; until the uncertainty is destroyed, then the outcome can be said to
&gt; exist.
">

Why? Presumably Schroedinger's cat knows if it is or is not dead, even
after the deed is done? We don't know till we open the box, but the
underlying pattern is, and shall be. Without that the cat's indeterminacy
can be asserted, but the fact remains, if the cat is alive, it knows it
whether we can or not.

Another way of looking at it is that two slit thing, Young's experiment. If
you accept that light can be a particle (as proven by the photoelectric
effect) the light has to know ahead of time where to land to contribute to
the interference pattern. OR, if you look at it as a wave, you can more
easily explain the interference, until you see that a single photon can
show this, though clearly it can't alone go through both slits. Either way,
the photon needs information that can't be reached within the time it has
for travel. That not only means that the old argument about wave/particle
duality is pointless, as light can't be either, but some 'thing' for want
of better term, that can appear as either, and possibly other 'things' we
haven't experienced or modelled, but it also means that its nature depends
on connections that 'travel' faster than it itself can.

That's the 'underlying pattern' I'm talking about. We can express it as a
probablility, but that's almost like a Spot The Ball competition, where the
only way to assert a location is by drawing on all the circumstantial
evidence pointing to it. Not that this is entirely bad, it is at least
thorough. It's almost the same as paraphrasing the Sherlock Holmes thing,
and saying &quot;when you have eliminated all overt possibilites, whatever
remains, no matter how covert, must be the truth.&quot; That's not ideal though.

Some truths can be proven by simple assertion and experiment, they don't
require probability to model them, no invocation of the unknown is needed.
The obvious is 2+2=4, but there are more interesting applied examples.

Case in point: The four-colour map problem. I was told that it is NOT
proven that four colours is the minimum required to colour a map without
adjacent regions being the same colour. I even asked a local university
mathematics professor why this was so. He told me he didn't know, that no-
one knew. My point is that if we have to 'prove' it by looking at all the
possible ways a map might be coloured, we can thrash through it eternally,
maybe. It's certainly intractable that way, but if you draw a circle on a
background, you have two regions, loop out and back to circle, that's
three, then loop out from the new arc and back to circle, that's 4. Now,
try again. You can't do it without isolating an existing region, which
means you can still colour all of them without using more than four
colours. That to me is a proof, so looking further to 'solve' that problem
is like walking into a room with a single lamp in it and looking at every
dark corner and saying no, the lamp is not there, before probablility is
eliminated leaving one location left for the lamp.

In short, as you can tell, probability bothers me, fundamentally, because
it isn't constrained to a limited set of conditions, except where those
conditions are ALREADY limited by our design, which is what bookmakers
depend on for a living, and even then it's still very risky. Card players
have better containment of possibilities... When trying to invoke it to
'explain' the universe at large, it boils down to saying 'we don't know'.
Which is ok, it's just that to enshrine it in grand theoretical terms looks
highly disingenuous, and I think that physics has not solved the hubris of
beleiving that everything can be explained in clocklike detail, it's just
found another way to state the old desire.
</POST>
