The only problem with Shrodingers cat is that the cat is an ordinary sized
object. The example of the cat is very bad, unless the cat is the size of an
atom. Then Shrodingers cat can indeed exists in both states indeterminately,
but this will never be the case for a real cat which is of normal size.

Shrodinger himself would use these examples to joke about the absurdities of
QM. The technical fallacy was applying a quantum scale property to an
ordinary sized objoct.

I'm not sure if it is desperation or not. In logic you have True and False
but there is no such thing as &quot;maybe&quot;. I dont know why there should'nt be.

Probability theory was developed pretty much simultaneously by the Soviets
and the West more or less independently during the 20th century. I dont
think that either development considers &quot;existential indeterminacy&quot;, and I
think that this must be a central issue for anyone who wants to invent his
own probability theory from scratch. Both treatments carefully sidestep this
issue, or construct arguments which make it possible to gloss over this very
glaring problem.

However, science has already adopted the fundamental philosophy, even if the
notational and algebraic constructions have not. Shrodingers cat is exactly
what I'm talking about. Ordinarily either LifeExists, or DeathExists, not
both. And Shrodingers cat violates this, you CAN have a mixed state where
you have that simultaneously : &quot;maybe&quot; LifeExists and &quot;maybe&quot; DeathExists.

Probability theory attempts to ignore this, so much so that in my opinion it
is really quite scandalous.

