The experiment is more wierd that that.

Imagine that you have some &quot;magic water&quot; which is behaving very strangely.
Sometimes it behaves like ice, and sometimes is behaves like liquid, and
this is completely unrelated to temperature or melting point.

If you ask &quot;how hard is it&quot;, or &quot;how syiff is it&quot;, then it will act like ice
for you, simply because you asked a question which requires it to do so.

But if you ask &quot;what is it's viscosity&quot;, then it obliges you by behaving as
a liquid, because you asked a question which requires that it be a liquid.

Now, instead of liquid-solid duality, I believe that there is a
continuous-discrete duality. The wave-particle duality is just a
continuous-discrete duality of space, and photons and other fundamental
particles are merely probabilistic wavefomrs in this dimensional fabric.

If you ask space a question which requires a discrete answer, it will act
like it is discrete.

But if you ask a question which expects an answer where the photon behaves
like a wave, then that is how space will answer you.

I should also state that this is not part of the standard model, and my
views are not mainstream physics.
